window.docContents[62].resolve({"/Class-Field-Theory-and-Galois-Theory/Power-residue-symbols/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Class-Field-Theory-and-Galois-Theory--Power-residue-symbols--The-Power-Residue-Symbol":{"contents":"Let  be a number field,  a primitive -th root of unity, and\n a prime of  whose absolute norm is coprime to . For\n with , the -th power residue symbol\nat  is the unique -th root of unity \ncharacterised by the congruence\n\nwhere  () is the absolute\nnorm. Existence and uniqueness of this root of unity come from the fact that the residue field\n contains a full set of -th roots of unity (since ) on which  lands; the symbol thus packages the action\nof the Frobenius (, ) on roots\nof unity, generalising the Legendre and Jacobi symbols.\nFormalised in power_residue_symbols: powerResidueSymbol — in progress (the uniqueness lemma exists_pth_root it depends on still contains a sorry).\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009Class Field Theory and Galois Theory\u0009Power residue symbols","header":"4.7.1. The Power Residue Symbol","id":"/Class-Field-Theory-and-Galois-Theory/Power-residue-symbols/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Class-Field-Theory-and-Galois-Theory--Power-residue-symbols--The-Power-Residue-Symbol"},"/Elementary-Number-Theory/Divisibility___-gcd___-and-the-fundamental-theorem-of-arithmetic/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Elementary-Number-Theory--Divisibility___-gcd___-and-the-fundamental-theorem-of-arithmetic--Bezout___s-Identity":{"contents":"(Bézout's identity.) For integers  and  there exist integers  and  with\n\nIn particular  is the smallest positive integer expressible as an integer combination of  and , and  and  are coprime iff  is such a combination.\n\nThe witnesses  and  are produced by the extended Euclidean algorithm, which runs the ordinary Euclidean algorithm while carrying along the coefficients expressing each successive remainder as a combination of  and . The integer statement reduces to the case of natural-number arguments, where the loop invariant of the extended algorithm is exactly the identity ; the four sign cases for the signs of  and  follow by substituting negations.\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009Elementary Number Theory\u0009Divisibility, gcd, and the fundamental theorem of arithmetic","header":"1.1.1. Bezout's Identity","id":"/Elementary-Number-Theory/Divisibility___-gcd___-and-the-fundamental-theorem-of-arithmetic/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Elementary-Number-Theory--Divisibility___-gcd___-and-the-fundamental-theorem-of-arithmetic--Bezout___s-Identity"},"/Fermat___s-Last-Theorem-and-Regular-Primes/Reduction-to-modularity/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Fermat___s-Last-Theorem-and-Regular-Primes--Reduction-to-modularity--Wiles___s-Reducibility-Theorem-for-the-Frey-Curve":{"contents":"(Wiles, Taylor–Wiles, Ribet.) For a Frey package and its Frey curve (), the mod  Galois representation ()  is not irreducible.\nFormalised in FLT: Wiles_Frey — in progress.\n\nThis is the deep half, the modularity route. The Frey curve's mod  representation is hardly ramified (good reduction away from the primes dividing , multiplicative reduction there with ). If  were irreducible, a modularity lifting theorem would make it modular, hence attached to a weight- newform of a level so small (after Ribet's level-lowering) that no such form exists. The Imperial project develops this through a general automorphy approach working directly with the -torsion; the modularity lifting input is still being formalised, so the statement reduces to in-progress automorphy results.\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009Fermat's Last Theorem and Regular Primes\u0009Reduction to modularity","header":"8.14.4. Wiles's Reducibility Theorem for the Frey Curve","id":"/Fermat___s-Last-Theorem-and-Regular-Primes/Reduction-to-modularity/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Fermat___s-Last-Theorem-and-Regular-Primes--Reduction-to-modularity--Wiles___s-Reducibility-Theorem-for-the-Frey-Curve"}});